        "body": "The opening line of Psalm 110 is one of the most theologically loaded sentences in the Old Testament. *Neum YHWH la-adoni* — literally 'oracle of YHWH to my lord.' *Neum* is the technical prophetic word for a divine utterance; the same formula introduces oracles in Isaiah and Jeremiah. David is functioning as a prophet (cf. Acts 2:30), reporting what he has been given to hear. And what he hears is a conversation in which YHWH addresses a figure David calls *adoni* — *my lord*, *my master*, *my sovereign*.\n\nJesus puts the weight of His messianic claim on this single line. In Matthew 22:41-46 (parallel in Mark 12 and Luke 20), He asks the Pharisees how the Messiah can be both David's son and David's Lord. The puzzle is unsolvable on standard Jewish-monarchical assumptions — a father does not call his descendant 'my lord.' The only solution is the incarnation: the Messiah is genuinely David's biological descendant *and* genuinely David's preexistent, divine superior. The Pharisees fall silent. They have no answer because the answer is the deity of Christ.\n\nThe content of the oracle is enthronement: *sit at My right hand*. The right hand of the king was the place of supreme honor — the position from which Bathsheba was offered a throne (1 Kings 2:19) and from which the firstborn received the chief blessing (Genesis 48:13-14). To sit at YHWH's right hand is to occupy the position of cosmic co-regency. Peter at Pentecost (Acts 2:33-35) and Hebrews 1:3, 13 identify this enthronement as the *ascension* — the moment when the resurrected Jesus took His seat at the Father's right hand. The session is not a future event; it has already happened.\n\nBut the session is bracketed by an *until*. 'Sit at My right hand *until* I make Your enemies a footstool for Your feet.' The footstool image is drawn from ancient Near Eastern coronation iconography — Egyptian and Assyrian reliefs depict kings literally resting their feet on the necks of subdued foes. Joshua's commanders place their feet on the necks of the five Amorite kings in Joshua 10:24. The image promises *total* subjugation. But the temporal marker *until* tells us this subjugation is in process. Christ is enthroned; His enemies are being subdued; the consummation is future. Hebrews 10:12-13 reads precisely this way: 'He, having offered one sacrifice for sins for all time, sat down at the right hand of God, waiting from that time onward until His enemies be made a footstool for His feet.' 1 Corinthians 15:25-26 names the last enemy: death itself, swallowed up at the resurrection.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** The verse hinges on two different words for 'Lord.' *YHWH* (the LORD, the covenant name) speaks; *adoni* (my lord, a non-divine honorific used widely in the OT) receives the speech. But verse 5 will use *adonai* — the divine title — of the same figure. The psalm thus distinguishes the two persons (YHWH and the Davidic Lord) while assigning divine dignity to both. The trinitarian implications are latent in the very vocabulary."
